oops.

00:06:06.700 --> 00:06:12.460
Okay. So I wanted to start with just a a couple of things to, kinda give kudos,

00:06:12.620 --> 00:06:15.420
to what's going on here in terms of curriculum and instruction.

00:06:16.465 --> 00:06:17.665
For a while,

00:06:18.145 --> 00:06:20.785
we focused a little bit on COVID.

00:06:20.785 --> 00:06:22.545
We focused on the

00:06:23.825 --> 00:06:26.865
the things that we had to ensure

00:06:26.865 --> 00:06:27.985
we regained

00:06:28.490 --> 00:06:29.370
after,

00:06:29.530 --> 00:06:31.610
the March 2020 closure.

00:06:32.010 --> 00:06:36.490
I want us to look just very briefly at the academic growth. It's very strong.

00:06:37.450 --> 00:06:46.025
The enrollment is strong. The staff professional development is strong, and staff retention is excellent. We are really truly

00:06:46.265 --> 00:06:48.345
one of the few schools,

00:06:48.745 --> 00:06:51.625
not only in our local region here, but statewide,

00:06:51.865 --> 00:06:54.505
that can say that, not only did people stay,

00:06:54.825 --> 00:06:58.550
but when we did have openings from 2020 until now,

00:06:58.790 --> 00:07:03.110
we were able to fill them with highly qualified people. And so I feel very,

00:07:04.150 --> 00:07:06.470
grateful for the fact that our,

00:07:06.950 --> 00:07:15.535
our staff is full, and we haven't had a ton of openings during the course of the year where we had to fill in with substitutes because that really does affect

00:07:15.695 --> 00:07:16.895
the academics,

00:07:16.895 --> 00:07:18.015
and that affects,

00:07:18.255 --> 00:07:20.495
staff development to making sure that,

00:07:20.735 --> 00:07:24.015
staff is is prepared to implement instruction.

00:07:24.415 --> 00:07:26.095
So when we look at academic growth,

00:07:26.710 --> 00:07:39.110
I know that Taylor had presented this earlier in the year. We looked at our SPAC scores. And although, obviously, we're never where we wanna be exactly, we were very proud of the fact that we had about a 10% improvement

00:07:39.645 --> 00:07:44.285
over the year before, and we do attribute this to curriculum and instruction.

00:07:44.925 --> 00:07:49.405
We've had more differentiated instruction and individualized learning opportunities,

00:07:49.565 --> 00:07:55.880
which has allowed us to take a more laser focused approach to the strategies that are utilized within the classroom.

00:07:56.680 --> 00:07:59.000
We had an increased number of activities,

00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:00.920
for both remedial

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:01.640
students,

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:05.000
grade level students, and enrichment opportunities,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:06.920
and I think that this has made a big difference.

00:08:08.445 --> 00:08:23.850
All curriculum revisions and changes have been aligned to things that are scientifically based, things that are evidence based, just very thoughtful in nature. Not necessarily expensive, just thoughtful in nature. And that's been instrumental in the success of our students.

00:08:24.810 --> 00:08:30.010
Looking at benchmark assessments and other data points have also helped to drive the instruction,

00:08:30.170 --> 00:08:33.610
not just focusing on one point aspect scores,

00:08:34.145 --> 00:08:42.785
not just focusing on one grade, not just focusing on the the students of their cookie cutters within the middle, just really making sure that we look at a lot of different

00:08:43.105 --> 00:08:45.105
data points to drive the instruction.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:53.280
And one of the things that I'm really proud that Taylor and the teachers, we have a great learning teams going on here right now.

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:57.520
They have grade level planning that occurs weekly,

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:07.965
where the second grade and third grade teachers will get together. The fourth, fifth, and sixth grade teachers will get together and really make sure that we look at both, you know, vertical and horizontal alignment

00:09:07.965 --> 00:09:13.890
with our curriculum and instruction. Everybody kinda knows what's going on in everybody else's classroom and how

00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:22.770
they can reinforce and assist one another. If you're a third grade teacher, how can I make sure that I reinforce the second grade and the fourth grade at the same time?

00:09:23.970 --> 00:09:30.355
Grade level planning is not the only meeting that occurs. There are data team meetings that occur,

00:09:31.475 --> 00:09:32.195
weekly.

00:09:32.675 --> 00:09:38.740
There are grade level collaborative gatherings, and I call them collaborative gatherings because they don't always take place,

00:09:39.060 --> 00:09:45.300
in tailored office. Sometimes it's planning periods where teachers are elsewhere sharing and modeling.

00:09:46.020 --> 00:09:46.980
SRBI

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:50.580
meetings, which is that scientifically research based interventions,

00:09:51.155 --> 00:09:56.195
these meetings are very important to make sure that we are looking at,

00:09:56.915 --> 00:10:08.040
students and meeting them where they are now, but not keeping them there, making sure that as soon as they meet a certain benchmark, they move on. And, of course, the PPT process for special education.

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:11.560
Progress since last year,

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:13.400
when we look at enrollment.

00:10:13.880 --> 00:10:18.440
We're always very proud of this. Not that we have everything to do with who moves into the town,

00:10:19.375 --> 00:10:20.815
but I do think that,

00:10:21.375 --> 00:10:25.135
having a good school, having a good program is something that does draw

00:10:25.295 --> 00:10:28.655
people into the town. You know, in 2020,

00:10:28.655 --> 00:10:32.410
when I got here, you know, that was really the lowest enrollment

00:10:32.410 --> 00:10:36.970
for us. We were at, like, one seventy four that year. And there were a lot of factors

00:10:37.130 --> 00:10:42.250
that drove that, including COVID and including some people that were at that time still homeschooling.

00:10:42.970 --> 00:10:44.490
In 2021,

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:49.085
the enrollment had grown a little bit, It was slow and steady to one eighty three,

00:10:49.405 --> 00:10:51.405
and we always had that goal of 200.

00:10:51.645 --> 00:10:53.085
In 2022,

00:10:53.645 --> 00:10:58.605
we hit the the goal of two hundred, and we were holding steady there. As of October,

00:10:59.180 --> 00:11:03.820
November, I'm sorry, of this year, it says October here, but a couple started in November.

00:11:03.980 --> 00:11:05.260
We're at two fifteen.

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:07.020
And we anticipate

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:10.940
this enrollment for next year will be a solid two fifteen,

00:11:11.260 --> 00:11:13.075
and we absolutely

00:11:14.035 --> 00:11:15.475
think there's a possibility,

00:11:15.875 --> 00:11:18.275
when we look at k and k enrollment,

00:11:18.355 --> 00:11:19.955
that's that's our strongest,

00:11:20.195 --> 00:11:27.475
grade level right now in terms of numbers, that there's a possibility that we could be looking at two thirty to two thirty five by the end of next year.

00:11:30.150 --> 00:11:36.790
So in the long term, this not only affects us, but this does affect the middle and high school as well. And,

00:11:37.110 --> 00:11:48.055
again, we're here to try to support them as our kids move up. Our classes are bigger that are gonna be moving up. Right now, they're at their lowest as we were years ago,

00:11:48.775 --> 00:11:50.215
back in 2020.

00:11:50.375 --> 00:12:01.950
And so the AES population of three year olds, preschoolers, all the way on to grade six, we actually represent 60% of all of the students in pre k to 12 now in the town of Andover.

00:12:02.510 --> 00:12:03.150
So,

00:12:03.470 --> 00:12:04.430
it's great.

00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:09.310
All of you know when you come into the building for events that it's so nice to see

00:12:09.885 --> 00:12:14.365
hustle and bustle of the kids again. So so we mentioned that because

00:12:14.605 --> 00:12:19.005
we really wanna look to make sure that we continue with, the stellar,

00:12:19.325 --> 00:12:22.685
preschool program that we have now that's gonna feed into k and then one.

00:12:23.790 --> 00:12:26.750
This is likely to secure enrollment

00:12:26.750 --> 00:12:28.270
moving forward in the future.

00:12:30.110 --> 00:12:32.190
When we look at professional development,

00:12:32.830 --> 00:12:36.270
professional development has been very purposeful.

00:12:36.430 --> 00:12:43.055
Not that it wasn't in the past, but I think with Taylor and the leadership teams that we now have in the building,

00:12:44.255 --> 00:12:47.615
we look to make sure that we're not just going through the process.

00:12:48.015 --> 00:12:51.295
One of the things the board of education does is support our calendar.

00:12:51.455 --> 00:12:59.640
And you know two years in a row now, we've been very thoughtful in terms of looking at those PD days, as really important

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:15.085
to the development of the teacher who's in the classroom with the students. And so we never want a staff member to walk away from professional development and think, well, that was a waste of my time. We want them to walk away and say, I'm really excited to implement some of these things that I have learned.

00:13:15.325 --> 00:13:18.525
And so we've been focusing on the science of reading.

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:31.300
I know we mentioned this at the last meeting. We talked about the waiver that we had put in. When we look at the science of reading, what we're looking at is those five tenets, the phonics, the phonemic awareness, fluency,

00:13:31.835 --> 00:13:33.435
comprehension, and vocabulary.

00:13:33.995 --> 00:13:36.635
And just for anybody who wasn't at our last meeting,

00:13:37.355 --> 00:13:48.410
when they did look at our waiver, they said, you know, we agree that the program that you have now, not only checks the box, but is is a strong enough program in phonics and phonemic awareness and fluency.

00:13:48.890 --> 00:13:49.290
And,

00:13:49.850 --> 00:13:57.610
the only thing they did want us to make sure we focus on moving forward is to creating a a little bit more robust at the k three level

00:13:57.985 --> 00:14:06.385
reading comprehension vocabulary. So that's really where the professional development's going for the science of reading now is making sure that we make that even more robust.

00:14:07.185 --> 00:14:11.985
For social emotional learning, we are and we will continue through the 2425

00:14:11.985 --> 00:14:14.890
school year to focus on zones of regulation

00:14:15.050 --> 00:14:16.650
and PMT training.

00:14:17.130 --> 00:14:22.570
We know that it's not necessary to train every staff member on PMT,

00:14:22.570 --> 00:14:23.210
which is

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:25.370
de escalation strategies

00:14:25.370 --> 00:14:27.665
and if ever the need arises,

00:14:28.225 --> 00:14:29.425
for restraint

00:14:29.425 --> 00:14:30.385
and seclusion.

00:14:30.465 --> 00:14:31.025
But

00:14:31.505 --> 00:14:37.025
we wanna make sure that everybody within the building, because we are, in essence, one giant cohort.

00:14:37.185 --> 00:14:41.585
We wanna make sure that everybody has all of the professional development opportunities

00:14:41.585 --> 00:14:52.820
should they want them. So everybody who's required or mandated to have the PMT training has it. And anybody else who wanted to attend, we also made sure that they had that opportunity.

00:14:53.300 --> 00:14:54.740
Just like with CPR,

00:14:54.820 --> 00:14:59.015
which isn't on here as a PD, but any of the safety professional development.

00:14:59.495 --> 00:15:11.015
Of course, we have staff that must have it, and then we offer it to the rest of the staff. And as you guys know, that professional development has also spread down to grades five and six who are also

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:14.400
CPR and first aid trained and certified.

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:17.440
We continue to train in sensory

00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:32.325
integration and the use of our sensory resources for our kids. This was a huge growth area for us to recognize that it wasn't just OT and PT and special education teachers and social workers that could benefit from being trained in sensory integration

00:15:32.485 --> 00:15:33.205
because,

00:15:33.445 --> 00:15:40.460
our classroom teachers are with a fair number of our students that may need some of those strategies on a regular basis.

00:15:40.780 --> 00:15:44.460
And so that continues to evolve as we move along.

00:15:45.660 --> 00:15:47.660
The NIAC accreditation

00:15:47.660 --> 00:15:49.340
is in process right now.

00:15:50.645 --> 00:15:52.485
Normally and historically,

00:15:52.485 --> 00:15:53.525
here at AES,

00:15:53.765 --> 00:15:56.725
we had the preschool that was NIAC accredited.

00:15:57.685 --> 00:15:58.165
And

00:15:59.045 --> 00:16:02.085
through OEC as well, we have guidelines, but NIAC accredited.

00:16:02.245 --> 00:16:06.650
And we made the decision about eighteen months ago that,

00:16:06.970 --> 00:16:09.850
we really wanted pre k and kindergarten

00:16:09.850 --> 00:16:11.290
to be accredited.

00:16:12.410 --> 00:16:22.095
I felt that it not only gave us a little bit of a feather to our cap in that department since, really nobody in the area has a kindergarten that is accredited.

00:16:22.175 --> 00:16:23.775
But I also felt that that

00:16:24.415 --> 00:16:29.615
further aligns in terms of curriculum and instruction to making sure that we have,

00:16:30.095 --> 00:16:38.960
a pathway, that we have a curriculum. There are people that think, well, kindergarten and pre k, don't they just play? Well, actually, there's play involved,

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:45.680
and there's professional development that, a lot of our staff have attended, but, there is

00:16:46.275 --> 00:16:48.355
a method to teaching,

00:16:48.835 --> 00:16:50.355
play and instructions. So,

00:16:51.155 --> 00:16:55.395
I'm very excited about this. I know that this accreditation will go through in the next,

00:16:55.635 --> 00:16:56.195
year,

00:16:56.515 --> 00:16:59.235
and so we will then have accredited

00:16:58.980 --> 00:17:09.300
pre k and kindergarten classes. And I do believe that that is one of the reasons why, you know, we've gotten a lot of, calls about what our program offers

00:17:09.380 --> 00:17:10.900
because I think we're top notch in the area.

00:17:11.945 --> 00:17:18.025
We have been and we will continue to focus on building number sense and computational fluency as well through the number talks.

00:17:18.265 --> 00:17:30.890
Math is gonna be a lot more of a focus next year. Not that it, wasn't equal to reading this year, but the mandates for reading kind of made it so that we had to put that a little bit more on the front burner.

00:17:30.890 --> 00:17:35.450
But math does continue in terms of professional development as well.

00:17:37.130 --> 00:17:39.770
So curriculum and instruction within the budget.

00:17:40.655 --> 00:17:43.215
It's funny because this is so very important.

00:17:43.615 --> 00:17:47.855
If you ask the teachers, this is one of the most important things for them on a daily basis.

00:17:48.415 --> 00:17:49.215
However,

00:17:49.935 --> 00:17:54.655
it it really is the smallest portion. It's less than 1% of our overall budget.

00:17:55.270 --> 00:17:59.350
The current total is roughly about $29,000

00:17:59.510 --> 00:18:05.990
spent on curriculum and instruction, not on staff, not on salaries, directly on just curriculum instruction.

00:18:06.150 --> 00:18:08.870
And when we talk about those kinds of expenditures

00:18:09.465 --> 00:18:11.465
that are related directly

00:18:11.465 --> 00:18:14.185
and solely to curriculum and instruction,

00:18:14.345 --> 00:18:16.345
these are things like manipulatives.

00:18:16.345 --> 00:18:21.225
In a math class, for example, the things that they use to help them learn a strategy.

00:18:21.945 --> 00:18:22.905
Consumables.

